<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create Barrel Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Spawns simple knockable world items such as barrels, cones, bins, burning barrels, and explosive drums.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Create Barrel Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Create Barrel</Bold> Event Point is used to spawn simple knockable mission props.
        These are physical objects that can be placed around the map for decoration, hazards,
        clutter, mission staging, or environmental detail.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Despite the name, this Event Point is not limited to ordinary barrels. It can create several
        related object types, including traffic cones, bins, burning barrels, and explosive LOX-style
        drums like those seen in the Semtex mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_barrel_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Simple rule:</Run>
                <Run>
                    One Create Barrel Event Point spawns one object. If you want several barrels, cones, bins, or drums,
                    place several Create Barrel Event Points.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adding a Create Barrel Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To add one, click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel, select
        <Bold>Create Barrel</Bold> from the Event Point type list, and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The <Bold>Edit EventPoint</Bold> window opens with the normal common properties and a small
        Create Barrel-specific section.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_barrel_add_type.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Create Barrel uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point
        type, letter group, colour, position, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. The letter group and colour can be set
        however you prefer. For simple scenery placement, you may want to group similar props
        together so they are easy to hide, filter, or inspect later.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_barrel_common_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The object spawns at the Event Point position. Use <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold> to
        place it visually in the viewport. This is usually easier than typing world coordinates by
        hand.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Because these are physical props, place them somewhere sensible: on roads, pavements,
        warehouse areas, alleyways, construction zones, industrial lots, or wherever the scenario
        requires them.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_barrel_position.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Barrel Type
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Create Barrel has only one important type-specific setting: the object type to spawn.
        Choose the type that matches the scene or mission situation you are building.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_barrel_type_dropdown.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Barrel / Oil Drum</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Useful for industrial areas, alleys, factories, loading zones, storage yards, and general
        urban clutter. For example, if you are making an old factory with oil drums behind it, use
        this type.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Traffic Cone</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Useful for crime scenes, construction work, road blocks, traffic incidents, police activity,
        or areas where you want the player to read the scene as temporarily blocked or controlled.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Bin</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Useful for streets, alleys, shopfronts, housing areas, back lanes, and general city dressing.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Burning Barrel</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Useful for dark alleys, rough areas, homeless encampment-style scenes, industrial yards, or
        places where you want fire/light ambience.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">LOX / Explosive Drum</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Useful for explosive set pieces or mission hazards, such as the LOX-style drums seen in the
        Semtex mission. Use these carefully if the object is expected to behave as an explosive
        hazard.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    One object spawns per Event Point. The Count-style behaviour used by some other Event Points does not apply here.
                    To create a cluster of objects, copy and paste the Event Point or create several manually.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        For normal prop placement, the object should exist when the mission starts. Use the standard
        immediate trigger setup:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Triggered By:</Bold> None / Game Starts.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Listening Mode:</Bold> Active.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This causes the barrel, cone, bin, burning barrel, or explosive drum to appear as soon as the
        mission begins.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_create_barrel_trigger_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Practical Examples
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Old Factory or Industrial Yard</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Place several oil drums or barrels around loading areas, storage corners, and behind
        buildings.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Crime Scene or Traffic Incident</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Place traffic cones around a blocked road, crash scene, police area, or temporary hazard.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Back Alley or Street Dressing</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Place bins, barrels, and other knockable objects to make the city feel more lived-in.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Hazard or Explosive Encounter</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use LOX/explosive drums when you want a dangerous object or mission hazard. Test these
        carefully to confirm the gameplay effect matches what you expect.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Create Barrel Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>Create Barrel</Bold> and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose a letter group and colour that fits your organisation scheme.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold> and place the object in the viewport.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select the object type, such as barrel, cone, bin, burning barrel, or LOX/explosive drum.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>None / Game Starts</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Listening Mode</Bold> to <Bold>Active</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>OK</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Copy and paste the Event Point if you need multiple similar objects.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save and test the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

</FlowDocument>
